@daveaitel The open source element is important. Perhaps you'll make some suggestions here. 
Note the 10/9 deadline.
https://t.co/5JV5VPPUHs

@sampullara You might like: https://t.co/UxHBi6lbI4

The link doesn't seem to be very data driven or precise. For example, they say #1 is malware delivered by email and then are vague on which apps allow arbitrary code execution.

The claim that USB attacks are common seems far-fetched.

@PilotCCIE @CISAgov @RachelTobac That's exactly the attack scenario that FIDO prevents! We are finally able to stop blaming users for falling for a credential phishing attack, but only if we mandate FIDO auth.

I invite you to learn more about the protocol. Here's one place to start:
https://t.co/oqbjTm2n5j

@PilotCCIE @CISAgov The FIDO protocol protects you even when you do what the attacker says. Neat, eh? 

This video from @RachelTobac shows how that works:
https://t.co/xKkj2Lj4dn

@Kym_Possible Did they tell you not to click on ‚Äúsuspicious‚Äù links? 
And to avoid public Wi-Fi? 
And to use ‚Äúcomplex‚Äù passwords, but no mention of password managers?

@NSA_CSDirector Why don‚Äôt online services aggressively nudge users (esp enterprise users) to enable MFA? 
Our PSAs for MFA for the past decade have barely made a dent. 
Let‚Äôs get this fixed upstream.

@runasand @FiloSottile This looks very interesting!
I've historically purchased models with 16G RAM, and yes it's because of all the tabs.
For 32G and 64G models, I have to wonder if we've drifted bit too far from the idea that the real work takes place in the cloud. Thoughts?

@Tork_88 @likethecoins When I did this in the past, I made these types of scenarios clear to the leadership team and in frequent updates to staff via email and in all-staff meetings. They got it.
Embedded keys help also.
Starting a pilot can help reduce drama down the road.

@ericlaw Where's the tip jar to make it go faster?! üòÜ
I caught some HTTP traffic on my home network and discovered my wife's Chromebook didn't have the HTTPS setting enabled. We fixed it, but she shouldn't have been on HTTP at all. 
She was in danger, but didn't know it.üò±

@ericlaw Is there a roadmap I can read? 
I'm uncomfortable with the current "We'll know it's done when it's done" approach. I would like to see a date or other hard metric. 
It's time.

@ericlaw There are indeed a lot of efforts, but it's time to finish the job.
It's time to prioritize the safety of my father over the concerns of antique websites.
We need to worry more about the people who are silently put in danger, and less about a vocal minority of website owners.

@ericlaw Also, here's a tweet from last year:
https://t.co/El6nmrgbvU
What meaningful progress have we made in the past year? Honest question since I don't know.

@TychoTithonus At what point do they pull the trigger? 94%? 95% 96%?
I see "activity" and not "finishing the job".
It's time. Pull the trigger.

@eastdakota @dok2001 Maybe you can do a 5 minute executive to executive pitch video for IT and Security teams (or anyone really) to send to the CEO and board. 10% tech, 90% business value. 
Right of boom is expensive! 
Maybe @CISAJen could do a cameo?

@sawaba @BrettCallow @enigmaconf Related from me: 

https://t.co/OIiyhabyza

Feedback welcome.

@hkhanna Like this? 
https://t.co/mOA1hUGZ4R
"In March, FIDO announced it has figured out a way to store the cryptographic keys that sync between people‚Äôs devices, calling them 'multi-device FIDO credentials' or 'passkeys.'"

@dasali What a great conference talk that would make! "How we got to X%, and the tricks that took us to 100%"
I'd even accept a talk like "We did a rigorous analysis, including conducting user interviews, and here are our surprising results and recommendations for others".
Let's do this!

@hadsomething4it Awesome! We need to hear your journey! Publish! Share! 
Defenders unite!! 
üîëüîê

@fugueish @riskybusiness I've been begging people to migrate all users, especially admins, to FIDO for several years. When they get hacked, they shrug and conclude that they need more employee training, or better detection, etc. 
So few say, Let's just eliminate phishing as a vector entirely.
Bonkers.

@2xyo What about these?
https://t.co/zvNtcvoFEx

Also, what would a breach cost an organization? (investigation, lost productivity, tarnished reputation, etc) To eliminate the #1 vector of attack, it might be very inexpensive.

@sayrer You should have a few. I like these. 

https://t.co/zvNtcvoFEx

https://t.co/rLno8TE7f6

@nicoleperlroth Good habits are hard to form and don‚Äôt happen overnight. And you can‚Äôt exercise for 24 hours straight once a year to get fit. 
We‚Äôve had years to get more than 30% of admins to use MFA. 
I wonder how we change the incentives to make better habits.

@wompdev @_mwc Training can be an important tool, but has a limited shelf-life. At work, I've worked to deploy systems that were safe by default, like Chromebooks and FIDO security keys. 
Feel free to check out this doc on how I think about advice:
https://t.co/Sz7NXMNcPN

@alt_tag @EveningStarIT @DougBarbin Ah, memory safety bugs! üò±üò© Why are C/C++ still legal?ü§£
As defenders, we should be focusing the spotlight of people's attention on the behaviors and tasks that blunt the most common attacks first. That's why I push this security checklist so hard:
https://t.co/SDrXMoMdzQ

@EveningStarIT @DougBarbin For sure! All software has bugs, and some of those bugs are security bugs. üò±

Cybersecurity is about risk management. People get hacked every second, but not by scanning QR codes. That's why I focus people's attention on these basics: https://t.co/SDrXMoMdzQ
Be safe!

@agowa338 @DougBarbin On my iPhone it shows that it's going to make a call with a phone icon and the phone number. 
The best practice is to use the phone's built-in QR code parser. They were pretty late to the game, but seem to be on it now. 
If there are other vulns let us know! Thanks!

@mattyrosen @MikeWiacek True, context can be important, like having one located in a place you expect to pay for something. But is that worse than having a shortened URL?

Also I take all those reports with a _huge_ grain of salt:
https://t.co/Ol1c4AGM4q

@radi_v @frgx @mrisher @verge @ashl3y_shen At this point in history, I would have hoped that we could use numbers as part of an overall plan to influence people to enable MFA.
Instead, we tell people to fret about airport wi-fi.
We need to turn that around. Keep pushing! üòÄüîêüôè

@tkejlboom @allan5oh Pinning does help, but it's required in most cases. 
It would be great if someone had a wall of shame for orgs not using things like pinning. 
(Your dog is lovely!)

@BigPipPinching If we can identify the website, it is easy to check on its configs.
This compromise (which I'm sure was painful!) is so close to normal, less-technical compromises like phishing, password reuse, compromise of the vendor, etc. 
Anything else should be a DEF CON presentation.

@jeremiahg related:
https://t.co/MDKKDnps4x

https://t.co/fWetLzfD0K

@QLDriver We point people to this checklist:
https://t.co/SDrXMoMdzQ
It covers both personal and work accounts for the reasons you cite. Feel free to forward (or remix under the CC license!)

@JimSycurity Agreed. The residual training should be:
1. How to escalate a potential security matter. Right-of-boom, everyone will have 20/20 hindsight.
2. How scams work, esp around BEC. I like using heists as a familiar model. People love a good heist!

@JohnHultquist Thanks for making this document public!
Small suggestions. First, try to eliminate the passive voice. Second, you might find some ideas in this post about giving security advice: https://t.co/Sz7NXMNcPN
But most importantly, THANK YOU!

@frgx @quentynblog They seem to go out of their way to not say "FIDO security keys" and instead use a vague description that could mean almost anything. 
How will they audit SSO MFA?

In any event, this is a good example of a company taking ownership for the security outcomes of their customers!

@frgx I suspect they are trying to make _progress_, but I'm suggesting they set a goal of 100% by some date this year. Mindset is everything. 
How about an opt-in dialog for 10% of all users? 
It's 2022. My dad has no business visiting an HTTP site, even if he tries. (Hi dad!ü§£)

@nicoleperlroth @ctll033 I'm biased, but I like this one (not political):
https://t.co/SDrXMoMdzQ 
üòá

@lisaphillips Good. It's weaker to say "Java is hated". By whom? 
"As of Friday morning, everyone in IT and Security hates Java" is better. 
A+
